{{nihongo|'''Eigo Fukai'''|深井 英五|Fukai Eigo|December 31, 1871 &ndash; October 21, 1945}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] businessman, central banker and the 13th Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ).

==Early life==
Fukai was born in [[Gumma Prefecture]].<ref>Bank of Japan (BOJ), [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/sousai13.htm/ 13th Governor]</ref>

==Career==
Fukai was the aide to [[Takahashi Korekiyo]], who was responsible for  negotiating war loans to pay for Japan's participation in the [[Russo-Japanese War]].<ref>Smethurst, Richard J. (1997). "Fukai Eigo and the Development of Japanese Monetary Policy," in ''New Directions in the Study of Meiji Japan,'' pp. 125-135.</ref>

Fukui was part of the Japanese delegation at the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Versailles Peace Conference]] in 1919.<ref name="nyt1935">[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/06/05/94618012.pdf  "Heads Bank of Japan; Fukai, Vice Governor, Is Promoted as Hijikata Retires,"] ''New York Times.'' June 4, 1935; retrieved 2011-08-22</ref>  He was a special appointee of the Foreign Office at the [[Washington Naval Conference|Washington Conference on Limitation of Armament]] in 1921.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/11/06/107031870.pdf  Personnel of Delegations ... Principal Delegates,"] ''New York Times.'' November 6, 1921; retrieved 2011-08-22</ref>  Fukui was also a Japanese delegate at the [[London Economic Conference]] in 1933.<ref>Byas, Hugh. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/05/04/99306152.pdf  "End to Trade Bars Desired by Japan; Fukai, Delegate to the World Parley, Declares Tariffs Should Be Reduced,"] ''New York Times.'' May 4, 1933; retrieved 2011-o8-22</ref>

Fukai was Governor of the Bank of Japan from June 4, 1935 – February 9, 1937.<ref>BOJ, [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/index.htm/ List of Governors].</ref>  His promotion came after seven years as Deputy Governor.<ref name="nyt1935"/>

During his term as head of the bank, his chief concern was ensuring confidence in Japan's currency and limiting [[monetary inflation]].  Ineffective efforts to slow the growth of military spending marked Fukai's term as BOJ governor.<ref>Kirshner, Jonathan. (2007). {{Google books|AYCBkDoSe1QC|''Appeasing Bankers: Financial Caution on the Road to War,'' p. 85.|page=85}}</ref>

